               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-833" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-833" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-833" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-833" type="given" value="PHILIP"></interp>PHILIP SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a painter, and live in Little Exeter-street, Lisson-grove. On the 25th of January, I was behind Mr. Savage's counter—the pri<lb></lb>soner came in for a pennyworth of pudding—he offered me a shilling—I called Mr. Savage, who came out and served him, and took up the shilling.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-834" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-834" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-834" type="surname" value="SAVAGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-834" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES SAVAGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I was called out of the parlour to give change for a shilling, which was on the counter—I took it up and laid it on a recess by it<lb></lb>self—the next day I gave it to a policeman—on the 26th a person came into my shop again—he offered me a bad shilling—I detained it—he left—I fol<lb></lb>lowed him—he joined the prisoner, and about a hundred yards further on, two more joined them—I then followed them to the Refuge for the Destitute—I kept the shilling—I pointed out the prisoner to the officer.</p>
               <p>
